"Indeed, Captain. They should already be on their way; they were still in the mess hall to pick up their rations."   At around 0500, the Exodus Company gathered at the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a box and began speaking.
"We will be relocated to forward deployment base I-131, fifty miles outside of Ianos. Our task is to support the ongoing siege and later the attack on Ianos to drive out the rebels. We will establish a foothold at the foot of the mountains there," Shaw explained. "Fall in with your squads and mount up."
The company broke up into the individual squads, and the soldiers were distributed onto the tanks by the sergeants. Cohren climbed into one of the tanks further up front in the convoy, where he met Nemec, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered their arrival a few days ago but knew little about them. He sat sideways and let his legs dangle while he adjusted his backpack and the communication device, which was connected to his headset and throat microphone.
"Hey Cohren, is Snowball still with Harris?" Nemic asked after they had settled in.
"Do you mean the rooster he stole?" Cohren remembered the morning when they had let the animal go on a farm. "Yes, I believe it was him."
Cohren looked over to one of the other tanks and spotted Harris with his squad. From the corner of his eye, he could make out the movement of a small chicken, which was constantly turning its head to search its surroundings.
"Yes, he is still with him," Cohren replied as the hatch of the tank opened and the commander came into view.
"Advance all tanks," the commander spoke slowly and calmly into his headset. The engines of the column of tanks and Strikers roared as they began to move. Cohren's Kronos tank jolted as the brakes were released and it fell into formation with the others. The tanks moved in a wedge formation across the Itania Plain. Despite the winter storms, the marsh areas were frozen and the forests snow-covered, yet mud was ubiquitous.
After about an hour, one of the recruits, whom Cohren knew was named Orson, began to speak. "Lieutenant, you've been here since the war began, right?"
" Yes, Operation Firestorm," answered Cohren. "We thought the matter would be taken care of in a few weeks, but we underestimated them."
"Underestimating them is vastly understated," Nemic interjected into the conversation. "We were not prepared for their arsenal of weapons and the sheer number of soldiers. They destroyed the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks and only the month ago did they destroy the Erebus. We should even expect to see them on our way."
"I stand firmly by the side of the Federation," said Orson defiantly. "I will not let these terrorists scare me."
"He is what you're saying now. But I've noticed that most eighteen-year-old recruits like you tend to take cover very quickly as soon as they hear a shot," Craith explained.
"The outcome will have to be seen," said Cohren laughing. Orson ended the conversation.
"Exodus XO, Exodus CO," crackled Cohren's radio. "We're picking up warmth signatures, about 300 meters away, 20 degrees to the right."
Cohren climbed onto the tank and put on his special glasses. When he switched them to "thermal imaging," he could recognize signatures in the distance.
"Yes, I see them," Cohren replied through his throat microphone.
"Are you hostile?" asked the other recruit, Natayla.
"Cannot identify," answered Cohren. He reached for his microphone and said: "Exodus Company, engage only if engaged. Let's lure them out."
As they approached, the dot-like heat signatures began to take shape. As they drew even closer, one of them ran hastily off to get something. She immediately returned to the small hill where the others were located. The figures lay down on the ground and went into firing position.
"We have enemy contact," Shaw called over the radio as orange tracer rounds were fired from the hilltop. While the tanks came under fire, the assault troops jumped down and took cover. A rocket flew past and struck the ground behind the formation, exploding and scattering debris onto one of the tanks. Another rocket struck a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. The crew quickly bailed out and sought cover as the ammunition went up in flames.
"Tank 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees right, 300 meters. Fire away," shouted the commander of the tank platoon over the radio. Tank 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, grenades flew towards the hill and exploded, throwing up mud and stone into the air.
"Send the Sentis in," called Knoxx, who was observing the hilltop with a telescope. The rear hatch of a Cerberus opened, and an unarmed soldier wearing a special headset emerged. He shouted commands into a square microphone, and two Sentis, officially named Sentinels, charged out. With their thin, metallic arms and legs swinging forward, they began running at a sprint. They carried their weapons on their backs.
"Kill or capture?" Craith asked as they watched.
"It looks like a capture," Cohren suspected as the two sentinels disappeared in the ash and smoke cloud. Yells and gunfire echoed from the hilltop, but quickly faded. A short time later, the two sentinels returned, dragging someone behind them whose boots left marks in the ground. After retreating back into the cover of their formation, they threw the figure onto the ground. The person groaned in pain as they landed hard in the mud and snow.
Shaw went to the figure that was just trying to stand up. Then he turned to one of the Sentinels. "How many?"
"Three dead, Sir," the Sentinel replied. "The rest fled on foot."
Shaw nodded and turned to Cohren and Craith, who were standing nearby. "Get this guy out of my sight!"
